					<h2>Culture, Stereotypes, and Identities<br> found in:<br><center>Movies & Books</center></h2>
				</div>
					<p>The literary works include movies and books created by professionals in the field of literature. These writers talk about culture, stereotypes and peoples identities. The movies and books I address include,  <i>The Piano Lesson</i> by August Wilson, <i>Smoke Signals</i> by Sherman Alexie, and  <i>The House on Mango Street</i> by Sandra Cisernos.
					Several Minority groups have had an extremely hard time in America and racial discrimination continues on today. I would like to address these issues in a moderate way, and again I wish to not offend anyone as this website is purely academic.
		
					</p>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3>Smoke Signals</h3>
						<p>Produced by Sherman Alexie, an American Playright.</p>
					<p>How do stereotypes affect who we think we are?<br>
					<br>The movie <i>Smoke Signals</i> gives us a forecast into the modern day Native American world.
					It is a fast paced emotional and hysterical film, which was very enjoyable to watch. 
					Written by a Native American, Sherman Alexie, the cast follows and is entirely Native American as well.
					In the movie, <i>Smoke Signals</i> there were several typical stereotypes of Native Americans.
					<br><br>Here are a list of some of the stereotypes portrayed in the movie:
					<ul>
						<li>Are supposed to look a certain way.</li>
						<li>Spiritually connected to nature and intuitively know their culture and history.</li>
						<li>Get assistance through casinos.</li>
						<li>Live on reservations.</li>
						<li>Lack an education.</li>
						<li>The stereotype that they live in teepees.</li>
						<li>That they are addicted to alcohol and drugs.</li>
					</ul>
					</p>
					<p>
					
						If the film does not specifically show individuals drunk, there are many references emphasizing it.
						Like the scene where his father burns down his own house because he is drunk and has fireworks.
						Not only does the film support these stereotypes, but it seems to easily make fun of the Native American culture.
						The stereotypes affected Victor in <i>Smoke Signals</i>by making him think that he should look a certain way.
						For instance, during the scene when Victor and Thomas were on the bus to Arizona, 
						Victor tells Thomas to stop acting like he is some type of “medicine man” and begins teaching him how to be “a true Indian.”
						Victor says to be “Indian” you have to have a certain facial expression and look a certain way: 
						“like you are warriors or just came from a buffalo hunt.”
						The idea of storytelling or oral traditions is also an important factor in the movie.
						The audience continually hears Thomas telling stories. It is not necessarily the story telling that is found funny, it is the way Thomas tells the stories; he acts like he is some kind of wise, astute man (as said before, like a medicine man). 
						There is another scene where they are told to go to the back of the bus because a man took their seat,
						feeling goofy, they sing about John Wayne having no teeth.
						I think this is funny because John Wayne has said some racist things in the past and 
						to get back at him they just made fun of his teeth with a song.
					<br>Overall, the movie seems to support many stereotypes of present day Native Americans.
