					<h3>The Piano Lesson</h3>
					<p>Produced by August Wilson, an American Playright.</p>
					
					<p>To what extent is our identity influenced by our family and community?<br> 
					<br>The Piano Lesson was a great lesson about African American culture.
					It is also a movie about self identities and how people portrayed themselves back in the day.
					Boy Willie wants to sell the piano to buy a plot of land, but Berniece will not part with piano because it holds a lot of their family history.
					The piano in the play represented the family’s history. 
					The family’s history was carved into the piano and their great grandmother 
					and grandfather were traded for it during Slavery. 
					Their father even died while he was trying to retrieve the piano from the old slaveowner Sutter’s house.
					Later on in the story Boy Willie tries to take the piano and it summons Sutter's ghost, to stop the ghost Berniece 
					had to play the piano and once she did it got rid of the ghost.
					I think that Boy Willie should have sold the piano because it was haunted and he could definently use that plot of land for his family.
					
					Berniece's identity was influenced by her family and community just by having the piano. The piano had so much history to it she thought she might as well keep it.
					The piano symbolizes slavery as well, and allows the family to grow stronger based on what had happened in their past. 
					The Piano Lesson had a hidden message that consists of the importance beyond material concerns, rather than a historical legacy. 
					The Piano Lesson conveys a message of learning as well and figuring out your true self. August Wilson says “that everyone has his or her own song.
					We must discover our songs.” This implies that everyone has their own unique ability, 
					and that we must discover what makes us the most passionate in this life based on our own ability.
					
					</p>
