					<h3>The House on Mango Street</h3>
				<p>	How can stereotypes affect our sense of pride, security, and independence?
					In the “House on Mango Street” written by Sandra Cisneros, I enjoyed several chapters of the book. The three chapters I liked the most were “My Name”, “Laughter” and “Those Who Don't". The main themes throughout this book portray culture, identity and stereotypes. Throughout the book Esperanza is constantly on the search for self identity. She is forced to move into a crowded Latino neighborhood in Chicago. There is racial segregation in this area and she starts discovering her true self. In the chapter “My Name” she talks about how she wants a different name and why it means so much to her. Later on in the book she hits puberty and both her grandfather and aunt pass away. This shows that she is maturing and how it affects her emotions as a maturing women. She learns about the true meaning of her life and sees how beautiful the world really is. These are exact examples of how she is trying to figure out her identity.</p>
